## Migration to typed provider resources

Per-cloud resources with a flatter schema are replacing the generic `yba_cloud_provider` resource. Migrate to the matching typed resource for your `code`:

| Old `code` | New resource |
|---|---|
| `aws` | [`yba_aws_provider`](aws_provider) |
| `gcp` | [`yba_gcp_provider`](gcp_provider) |
| `azu` | [`yba_azure_provider`](azure_provider) |

Migration steps for an AWS provider (the GCP and Azure flows are analogous):

1. Replace the `yba_cloud_provider` block with a `yba_aws_provider` block and lift the nested credential block:

    ```hcl
    # Before (deprecated)
    resource "yba_cloud_provider" "aws" {
      code = "aws"
      name = "aws-provider"
      aws_config_settings {
        access_key_id     = "<aws-access-key-id>"
        secret_access_key = "<aws-secret-access-key>"
      }
      regions { ... }
    }

    # After
    resource "yba_aws_provider" "aws" {
      name              = "aws-provider"
      access_key_id     = "<aws-access-key-id>"
      secret_access_key = "<aws-secret-access-key>"
      regions { ... }
    }
    ```

2. Move the existing resource state to the new address and re-import (state is not transferable across schemas):

    ```sh
    terraform state rm yba_cloud_provider.aws
    terraform import yba_aws_provider.aws <provider-uuid>
    ```

3. Run `terraform plan` and reconcile any drift. The typed resources drop the `code`, `dest_vpc_id`, `host_vpc_id`, and `host_vpc_region` fields. AWS region blocks use `vpc_id` (was `vnet_name`); GCP zones use `shared_subnet` (was `subnet`); other field names map one-to-one.

See [`yba_aws_provider`](aws_provider), [`yba_gcp_provider`](gcp_provider), and [`yba_azure_provider`](azure_provider) for the full schema of each typed resource.

## Import

Cloud Providers can be imported using `cloud provider uuid`:

```sh
terraform import yba_cloud_provider.cloud_provider <cloud-provider-uuid>
```
